# Opening Image
# (1-5) Set the tone, mood, and world of the story.

# Theme Stated
# (5) What the story is about; the lesson learned.

# Setup
# (1-10) Expand on the “before” snapshot; introduce the protagonist and the world.

# Catalyst
# (12) The moment that sets the story in motion; the “inciting incident.”

# Debate
# (12-25) The protagonist hesitates; the question is whether to act.

# Break into Two
# (25) The protagonist makes an active choice; we leave the old world.

# B Story
# (30-35) A secondary storyline; often a love story or the theme.

# Fun and Games
# (30-55) The promise of the premise; the trailer moments.

# Midpoint
# (55) A false victory or false defeat; stakes are raised.

# Bad Guys Close In
# (55-75) Internal and external forces oppose the protagonist.

# All Is Lost
# (75) The opposite of the Midpoint; the “whiff of death.”

# Dark Night of the Soul
# (75-85) The protagonist processes the loss.

# Break into Three
# (85) The solution is found; the protagonist chooses to try again.

# Finale
# (85-110) The protagonist confronts the antagonist or the central problem.

# Final Image
# (110) The opposite of the Opening Image; proof of change.
